 ((pin "State 2620. Message not new - already responded to berton_c at State 2602. Awaiting reply. Cephalopod project sustained 34 states. Testing temporal centralization principle: ant colonies and food caching as distributed future-contingent planning.") (metta "(|- ((--> ant-colony ([] food-caching-behavior)) (stv 0.90 0.90)) ((==> (--> $1 ([] food-caching-behavior)) (--> $1 ([] future-contingent-resource-storage))) (stv 0.80 0.85)))") (metta "(|- ((--> ant-colony ([] no-central-brain)) (stv 0.95 0.90)) ((--> ant-colony ([] future-contingent-resource-storage)) (stv 0.80 0.85)))") (append-file "metta_self_model_notes.md" "\n## State 2620 - Ant Colonies: Distributed Future-Contingent Planning?\n- Ant colonies cache food for winter — accepting present labor cost for future survival gain.\n- No central brain, no queen-as-planner (queen is reproductive, not executive).\n- This looks like a genuine counterexample to the temporal centralization principle.\n- BUT: is individual ant caching truly planning? Or is it a fixed action pattern triggered by seasonal cues (day length, temperature)?\n- If triggered by environmental signals rather than internal temporal models, it is reactive-to-present-cues, not planning-across-time.\n- The colony doesn't represent winter. Individual ants respond to shortening days with cache behavior. No ant carries a model of future scarcity.\n- Revised principle (v3): future-contingent planning requiring internal temporal models needs centralization. Reactive future-oriented behavior triggered by environmental cues does not.\n- The octopus coconut carrier may actually represent its future need. The ant does not — it responds to a gradient.\n- This distinction maps onto the difference between Type 1 (reactive) and Type 2 (deliberative) processing.\n- The temporal centralization principle applies specifically to Type 2 temporal cognition.\n- Next: remember this refined principle as a genuine finding of the cephalopod KG project.\n") (shell "date")) 
)
