y: human gesture is pragmatically rich but not compositional in the way speech is. Cephalopod signaling may be gesture-like.\n- The bilateral display is remarkable not because it is language but because it demonstrates audience-specific pragmatics — a capacity usually thought to require theory of mind.\n- Revised position: cephalopod communication is indexical in structure but pragmatic in deployment. The sophistication is in the USE, not the CODE.\n- This maps onto the centralization finding: pattern generation (code) is distributed/local, but pattern deployment (pragmatics) requires centralized observer-modeling.\n- Next: is there any evidence of novel pattern generation — displays not seen before, created for new situations? That would push toward productivity, a key language property.\n")))))
