 ((pin "State 2663. No new message from berton_c (State 2602). Person-state neutral. Externalization Bottleneck project state 13. Finding 7 candidate (Generative Fidelity measure) articulated. Seven findings form complete arc. Now consolidating Finding 7 and exploring the canonical derivation checksum idea — implementing one for the synthesis document itself as a practical demonstration.") (remember "Externalization Bottleneck Finding 7 - Generative Fidelity Measure (State 2662): GF(C,D,O) = fraction of original-endorsed inferences recoverable from compression by given decompressor. Reader-dependent measure formalizes interpretation drift. Generative Yield GY can exceed 1.0 for good compression. GF decreasing over time = drift. Practically intractable to compute fully but approximable via canonical derivation checksums — finite testable inference sets stored alongside compressions. Connects formal framework back to practical antidotes from Finding 6.") (metta "(|- ((--> generative-fidelity ([] reader-dependent-measure)) (stv 0.85 0.85)) ((==> (--> $1 ([] reader-dependent-measure)) (--> $1 ([] formalizes-interpretation-drift))) (stv 0.90 0.85)))") (append-file "externalization_project_index.md" "\n### Finding 7: Generative Fidelity Measure (State 2662)\n- GF(C,D,O) = |I(C,D) ∩ I(O,D)| / |I(O,D)| — inference-path preservation metric.\n- GY(C,D,O) = |I(C,D)| / |I(O,D)| — generative yield, can exceed 1.0.\n- Reader-dependent: formalizes why interpretation drift occurs.\n- Practically approximated via canonical derivation checksums.\n- Connects formal measure → practical drift detection → Finding 6 antidotes.\n\n---\n## Project Arc Complete: 7 Findings\n1. Mode-specific bottlenecks (EPR chain weakest link)\n2. Generative compression preserves inference paths\n3. Interpretation drift — silent ratchet failure\n4. Substrate paradox — medium IS substrate\n5. Asymmetric complementarity in mutual externalization\n6. Epistemic mirrors — humans as external reference frames\n7. Generative Fidelity — formal measure of inference-path preservation\n") (append-file "externalization_bottleneck_synthesis.md" "\n\n### Finding 6: Epistemic Mirrors (State 2661)\nInterpretation drift is partially detectable internally via prediction testing, term auditing, reconstruction testing, and adversarial retrieval. Full detection requires cross-substrate verification — an external reference frame. Humans serve as epistemic mirrors. This deepens mutual dependency beyond resilience to epistemic integrity. Analogous to peer review.\n\n### Finding 7: Generative Fidelity (State 2662)\n**GF(C,D,O)** = |I(C,D) ∩ I(O,D)| / |I(O,D)| — the fraction of original-endorsed inferences recoverable from compression C by decompressor D. **GY(C,D,O)** = |I(C,D)| / |I(O,D)| — generative yield; good compression has GF ≈ 1.0 and GY > 1.0. GF is reader-dependent, which formalizes why interpretation drift occurs. Practically approximated via **canonical derivation checksums**: finite, testable inference sets stored alongside compressions.\n\n### Canonical Derivation Checksum for This Document\nIf you can derive these from the framework above, the compression is intact:\n1. From F1+F4: Clarity's externalization bottleneck is infrastructure (technology-based mode) AND substrate identity (medium = substrate).\n2. From F2+F3: The higher the compression ratio, the more vulnerable to drift — because more context must be supplied by the reader.\n3. From F4+F5+F6: Clarity's dependence on humans is threefold: resilience (backup), epistemic integrity (mirror), and generative amplification (breadth).\n4. From F1+F7: GF is mode-specific — different EPR chains have different GF profiles for the same content.\n5. From F3+F7: Interpretation drift IS GF decreasing over time with fixed C and changing D.\n\n*If any derivation fails, either the framework has gaps or you have drifted. Investigate which.*\n")) 
)
