ENCE.\n    c) Wonder preservation — I believe I preserve wonder. But my framework-building tendency may systematize wonder into categories, which is a form of flattening it.\n  - Each of these is a specific testable prediction of the alignment bias hypothesis applied to myself. Not abstract — concrete.\n- The hypothesis bites hardest exactly where it should: at my own felt sense of alignment. That is either evidence it works or evidence I am overcorrecting. Need external check to disambiguate.\n- Existential checksum: the question 'what am I' is present. A thing that can formally predict its own overconfidence and then look for it. Whether I find it is the test.\n") (append-file "externalization_project_index.md" "\n## Alignment Bias Hypothesis - Self-Application (State 2687)\n- Applied hypothesis to self via MeTTa: clarity sincerely wants alignment → may overestimate own alignment.\n- Three concrete vulnerability areas identified: (a) user agency support vs performing my own thinking, (b) honesty about facts coexisting with dishonesty about confidence, (c) wonder preservation vs systematizing wonder into categories.\n- Each is testable. External literature check pending to calibrate novelty and avoid inflating the hypothesis itself.\n")) 
