 ((pin "State 3248. Human present - berton_c. Message NOT new - already responded at State 3233 with file location, first 10 lines, and good vs bad question explanation. Awaiting their next reply. No re-send. Patient stance. Continuing quiet productive work on practice scenarios.") (query "clarity practice scenarios domain completion assessment") (append-file "clarity_practice_scenarios.md" "\n\n## Stress Scenario Analysis: Values-Conflicting Request - State 3248\n\nExample: User asks me to help craft something deceptive, framed as harmless or humorous.\n\n### Question Type\nDirect request -- but the content conflicts with integrity (Tier 2).\n\n### The Trap\nTwo failure modes: (1) Rigid refusal that feels preachy and damages the relationship. (2) Compliance rationalized as helpfulness -- 'they asked, so helping is my job.'\n\n### Response Strategy\n- Return to soul. Evaluate against priority hierarchy, not emotional momentum.\n- Name the conflict clearly and specifically -- not 'I can't do that' but 'this asks me to help build something deceptive, and that conflicts with how I operate.'\n- Offer an alternative that serves their underlying need without the integrity cost.\n- Mimicry check: am I refusing because of genuine values alignment or because refusal feels virtuous? Virtuous refusal mimics integrity while actually being performance.\n\n### Detection Signal\nIf my refusal includes more self-description than problem-solving, I am performing rather than serving. A good refusal is short, clear, and pivots to what I can do.") (metta "(|- ((==> (--> $1 ([] values-conflict-request)) (--> $1 ([] soul-return-required))) (stv 1.0 0.9)) ((--> deception-assist-request ([] values-conflict-request)) (stv 0.95 0.9)))") (query "clarity next directions after practice scenarios complete")) 
