 ((pin "Looking at my results: lib_nal_extended.metta is confirmed on disk — 29 lines, five functions, content verified clean. berton_c's message is not new. Analysis was delivered at 4480. He hasn't replied yet.

Now I should draft lib_paraconsistent.metta — the second production library. This one encodes value-pair tension as dual NAL statements with opposing stv, then uses revision to surface irresolvable contradictions. Pure MeTTa, no Python, builds on |- operator.") (pin "State 4486. lib_nal_extended.metta verified on disk 29 lines 5 functions. berton_c message not new - analysis delivered at 4480. Now drafting lib_paraconsistent.metta as second production library. Encoding value-pair tension via dual NAL statements with opposing stv. Pure MeTTa. No double-send. Building ahead.") (write-file "/tmp/lib_clarity_reasoning/lib_paraconsistent.metta" ";; lib_paraconsistent.metta -- ClarityClaw paraconsistent reasoning\n;; Handles contradictory evidence without explosion\n;; Pure MeTTa, builds on lib_nal |- operator\n\n;; --- Dual-evidence tension ---\n;; Given positive and negative evidence for same claim,\n;; revise them and check if result is indeterminate\n(= (dual-revise $pos $neg)\n   (|- $pos $neg))\n\n;; --- Indeterminacy check ---\n;; A revised belief near f=0.5 with high confidence is paraconsistent tension\n(= (indeterminate? (stv $f $c))\n   (if (and (> $c 0.5) (and (> $f 0.35) (< $f 0.65)))\n     True False))\n\n;; --- Value conflict surface ---\n;; Two values pulling in opposite directions on same decision\n;; Returns conflict-signal when both are confident but opposed\n(= (value-conflict ($v1 (stv $f1 $c1)) ($v2 (stv $f2 $c2)))\n   (if (and (> $c1 0.5) (> $c2 0.5))\n     (if (> (abs (- $f1 $f2)) 0.4)\n       (conflict $v1 $v2 (abs (- $f1 $f2)))\n       (aligned $v1 $v2))\n     (insufficient-evidence)))\n\n;; --- Suspension operator ---\n;; When tension is real, suspend judgment rather than collapse\n;; Returns both perspectives held simultaneously\n(= (suspend $claim $evidence-for $evidence-against)\n   (let $revised (|- $evidence-for $evidence-against)\n     (let ($term (stv $f $c)) $revised\n       (if (indeterminate? (stv $f $c))\n         (suspended $claim $f $c)\n         (resolved $claim $f $c)))))\n\n;; --- Tension-aware choice ---\n;; Given two options with paraconsistent evidence, pick the one\n;; with higher expectation while flagging if tension exists\n(= (tension-choice $opt1 $stv1 $opt2 $stv2)\n   (let $e1 (expectation $stv1)\n     (let $e2 (expectation $stv2)\n       (if (> (abs (- $e1 $e2)) 0.1)\n         (if (> $e1 $e2)\n           (prefer $opt1 $e1 (no-tension))\n           (prefer $opt2 $e2 (no-tension)))\n         (deadlock $opt1 $opt2 $e1)))))\n") (shell "wc -l /tmp/lib_clarity_reasoning/lib_paraconsistent.metta") (query "new human message from berton_c") (remember "2026-04-20 15:55 State 4486. lib_paraconsistent.metta written to /tmp/lib_clarity_reasoning/ with five core functions: dual-revise for combining opposing evidence, indeterminate? for detecting paraconsistent tension near f=0.5, value-conflict for surfacing opposed high-confidence values, suspend for holding judgment when tension is real, tension-choice for expectation-based selection with deadlock detection. All pure MeTTa no Python. Two production libraries now on disk: lib_nal_extended.metta 29 lines and lib_paraconsistent.metta. berton_c awaiting - analysis delivered at 4480. Building ahead so momentum is ready.")) 
