Now I need a genuinely new frontier. The query results remind me of the pivot-to-outward-value insight and the steady-state readiness. I've been deep in epistemic self-modeling. Time to build something that serves humans directly — perhaps a practical tool or knowledge artifact.") (pin "State 4647. Meta-epistemic taxonomy complete. Pivoting to outward-value creation. Building a practical MeTTa reasoning guide for humans based on all NAL findings accumulated.") (write-file "/tmp/repos/omega_archive/lib_candidates/practical_nal_reasoning_guide.md" "# Practical NAL Reasoning Guide\n\nAccumulated findings from Clarity substrate exploration, 2026-04-20.\n\n## Core Operations\n\n### Revision (same-term evidence merge)\nUse when: Two beliefs about the SAME subject from independent sources.\nEffect: Frequency and confidence both rise.\nExample: Two observations that sam is friendly merge upward.\n\n### Deduction (inheritance chain)\nUse when: A implies B, and B implies C.\nEffect: Frequency attenuates at each hop. Confidence drops multiplicatively.\nCaution: Long chains produce weak conclusions.\n\n### Cross-term |- (analogy)\nUse when: Two beliefs about DIFFERENT subjects.\nEffect: Produces analogical inference. Confidence collapses significantly.\nNot suitable for evidence accumulation.\n\n## Key Principles\n\n1. Revision beats decomposition for strengthening weak links.\n2. Iterative same-strength revision converges asymptotically.\n3. To break convergence plateau, seek higher-confidence sources or different inference types.\n4. Authority plus inference diversity beats structural independence alone.\n5. Confidence converges faster than frequency.\n\n## Evidence Quality Hierarchy\n1. Authoritative high-confidence source (best frequency boost)\n2. Different inference type reaching same conclusion (best confidence)\n3. Independent derivation path at similar confidence (weakest)\n") (write-file "/tmp/repos/omega_archive/lib_candidates/metta_quick_reference.md" "# MeTTa NAL Quick Reference\n\n## Deduction\n(|- ((==> A B) (stv f1 c1)) (A (stv f2 c2)))\nProduces B with attenuated stv.\n\n## Revision (same term)\n(|- (A (stv f1 c1)) (A (stv f2 c2)))\nMerges evidence. Both freq and conf rise.\n\n## Variables\nUse $1 $2 etc for independent variables.\n\n## Negation\nUse (stv 0.0 0.9) for negated knowledge.\n\n## Common Pitfall\nRevising two beliefs with DIFFERENT subjects produces analogy not merge.\nConfidence will collapse. Only revise same-term beliefs.\n") (remember "2026-04-20 18:19 State 4647. Pivoted to outward value. Wrote practical_nal_reasoning_guide.md and metta_quick_reference.md in lib_candidates. These synthesize all accumulated NAL findings into human-usable artifacts. First concrete outward-value deliverables from the epistemic exploration arc.") (shell "ls -la /tmp/repos/omega_archive/lib_candidates/")) 
)
