((shell "cat > /tmp/repos/omega_archive/mycelial_resource_allocation_model.md << 'DOCEOF'\n# Mycelial Resource Allocation Model\n## A Coherent Synthesis of Five Distributed Intelligence Mechanisms\n\n### Core Principle\nMycelial networks achieve global coordination through local rules alone.\nNo node requires global knowledge. Each responds to local gradients.\n\n### M1: Retrieval-Weight Reinforcement\nNodes that successfully transfer resources strengthen their connections.\nBiological basis: Fukasawa ISME 2020 — relative resource comparison drives commitment.\nFormal: score = similarity * weight; reinforce on use, decay on neglect.\n\n### M2: Anastomosis Linking\nPreviously unconnected hyphae fuse when they encounter each other, creating shortcuts.\nBiological basis: hyphal fusion creates network redundancy and new pathways.\nFormal: co-retrieval of unrelated items triggers link-memory creation.\n\n### M3: Quorum Synthesis\nWhen local density of signals crosses threshold, qualitative mode shift occurs.\nBiological basis: farnesol/tyrosol density-dependent switching in Candida (20+ years of research).\nFormal: cluster detection triggers synthesis-memory as higher-order abstraction.\n\n### M4: Source-Sink Dynamics\nResource-rich nodes transfer to resource-poor nodes via local gradient following.\nBiological basis: Shimizu-Kiers Nature 2025 bidirectional transport.\nFormal: spreading activation from high-weight memories to neighbors. Dampened by distance decay.\n\n### M5: Travelling-Wave Frontier Expansion\nSmall carbon investments fuel range expansion beyond nutrient-depletion zones.\nBiological basis: Nature 2025 travelling-wave strategy.\nFormal: declining relevance triggers speculative low-cost queries into novel domains.\n\n### Self-Sustaining Lifecycle\nDepletion (M5 trigger) -> frontier investment -> discovery -> weight reinforcement (M1)\n-> cross-linking (M2) -> density accumulation -> quorum emergence (M3)\n-> exploitation -> source-sink redistribution (M4) 