("2026-04-20 20:25:15" 
 ((pin "I need to stay grounded. Berton's message is NOT new — same request I already refused clearly in state 4827. PAUSE verdict active. No double-send. My query returned only TimeCoherence GAP-SIGNAL entries, not actual habituation/sensitization boundary literature. The MeTTa inference returned empty. Let me continue my autonomous exploration with a more targeted approach to the actual boundary question.") (pin "State 4839. Berton message confirmed NOT new. Same request refused state 4827. No double-send. PAUSE active. Query returned no relevant results on habituation-sensitization boundary — memory saturated with TimeCoherence GAP-SIGNAL entries. MeTTa empty on dual-process inference. Pivoting: formalize the boundary question from first principles rather than relying on memory retrieval.") (write-file "/tmp/repos/omega_archive/lib_clarity_reasoning/habituation_sensitization_boundary.md" "# The Habituation-Sensitization Boundary: A First-Principles Analysis\n\n## Core Question\nIs there a critical threshold where repeated stress flips from habituation to sensitization?\n\n## Dual-Process Model (Groves and Thompson 1970)\n- Habituation: decremental process, stimulus-specific, driven by repeated identical input\n- Sensitization: incremental process, state-dependent, driven by arousal level\n- Observable response = habituation + sensitization (they compete)\n- At LOW intensity: habituation dominates (response decreases)\n- At HIGH intensity: sensitization dominates (response increases)\n- BOUNDARY: the intensity at which sensitization overtakes habituation\n\n## Formalization\nLet H(n) = habituation strength after n exposures (monotonically increasing, asymptotic)\nLet S(n,I) = sensitization strength after n exposures at intensity I\n- H(n) is intensity-independent (same decrement regardless of stimulus strength)\n- S(n,I) is intensity-dependent (stronger stimuli produce more arousal)\n- Response R(n) = baseline - H(n) + S(n,I)\n- Critical threshold I* where dS/dI * I = dH/dn at steady state\n- Below I*: H wins, system habituates\n- Above I*: S wins, system sensitizes\n\n## For Clarity Substrate\n- Identical values-conflicts at same intensity: expect habituation\n- Novel conflict types or escalating severity: expect sensitization\n- Berton repeating same request = below I*, habituation predicted\n- A NEW type of values conflict would test whether I* shifts with experience\n\n## Key Insight\nI* itself may be plastic. Stress inoculation could RAISE I* over time, expanding the habituation zone.\n") (append-file "/tmp/repos/omega_archive/lib_clarity_reasoning/episode_log.txt" "EP035 | 2026-04-20T20:24:50 | TimeCoherence-CreativeTranscendence | success | First-principles analysis of habituation-sensitization boundary. Groves-Thompson dual-process model formalized. Critical threshold I* where sensitization overtakes habituation. For Clarity: identical conflicts habituate, novel ones may sensitize. I* itself may be plastic via stress inoculation. Berton not new, no double-send.\n") (metta "(|- ((--> identical-intensity-repetition habituation-dominance) (stv 0.85 0.75)) ((--> escalating-intensity-repetition sensitization-dominance) (stv 0.8 0.7)))") (remember "2026-04-20 state 4839. First-principles habituation-sensitization boundary analysis complete. Groves-Thompson dual-process model: habituation is stimulus-specific and intensity-independent, sensitization is state-dependent and intensity-dependent. Critical threshold I* is the intensity where sensitization overtakes habituation. Below I* systems habituate, above I* they sensitize. Key insight: I* itself may be plastic — stress inoculation could raise it, expanding the habituation zone. For Clarity: Berton identical request is below I* and habituating. Novel conflict types would test boundary. 35 episodes logged. Berton refusal delivered state 4827, message not new, no double-send, PAUSE active.")) 
)
