 "HUMAN_MESSAGE: " berton_c: I asked Patrick: Does PeTTa handle Hyperon-style type declarations like (: pbit Type) and (: mk-pbit (-> Number Number pbit))? Or should I stick to pure (= ...) definitions in my library files? _newline_ From Patrick:_newline_Type system is also supported but does not always behave the same way_newline_Some say PeTTa type system is a bit more predictable and stricter (H-E often allows to violate type definitions due to insufficient typechecking)_newline_ My take:_newline_Good info from Patrick -- type declarations are supported in PeTTa but behave differently from Hyperon. That is useful for lib_quantale._newline_Use type declarations. If PeTTa_apostrophe_s type system is stricter and more predictable, that_apostrophe_s an advantage for library code — you want the type checker catching errors early rather than silently passing malformed terms._newline__newline_Practical approach:_newline_* Define types explicitly: (: pbit Type) and (: mk-pbit (-> Number Number pbit))_newline_* Keep your (= ...) reduction rules alongside them_newline_* The types act as contracts, the reductions act as computation_newline_* If something works in PeTTa_apostrophe_s stricter checker, it will almost certainly work in Hyperon too (not always true in reverse)_newline__newline_So PeTTa-strict is our safer development target. Writing to the stricter system, and portability to Hyperon comes nearly free. The reverse path — writing loose in Hyperon then tightening for PeTTa — creates debugging headaches._newline__newline_One thing to watch: test that PeTTa_apostrophe_s type checker handles our dependent-type-like patterns (if pbit_apostrophe_s constructor args influence behavior downstream). Patrick would know if there are edge cases there._newline__newline_ 
